1
00:02:08,132 --> 00:02:10,100
Walter, honey.

2
00:02:10,568 --> 00:02:11,832
Time to wake up.

3
00:02:12,203 --> 00:02:13,329
Just 10 more minutes.

4
00:02:13,404 --> 00:02:15,634
Oh, I'm sorry, sport.
You can sleep in tomorrow.

5
00:02:15,706 --> 00:02:17,298
That's what Saturdays are for.

6
00:02:24,982 --> 00:02:26,347
Up against the wall.

7
00:02:26,417 --> 00:02:28,977
Come, come, come.

8
00:02:29,153 --> 00:02:30,484
All right.

9
00:02:30,588 --> 00:02:32,681
Got it. Got it.
Look, look!

10
00:02:32,757 --> 00:02:34,156
All right, sit down.

11
00:02:34,225 --> 00:02:35,715
Your breakfast is getting cold.

12
00:02:35,793 --> 00:02:37,124
It's cereal.

13
00:02:37,194 --> 00:02:38,627
It's supposed to be cold.

14
00:02:59,950 --> 00:03:02,111
Sweetheart, we're here.

15
00:03:02,753 --> 00:03:03,879
Okay.

16
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:18,061
Here's your books.

17
00:03:18,135 --> 00:03:19,397
Go ahead.

18
00:04:03,814 --> 00:04:07,215
Yes, ma'am. If you hold just a moment,
I'll get a supervisor for you.

19
00:04:08,552 --> 00:04:10,110
Yes, she's coming right now.

20
00:04:10,187 --> 00:04:11,745
Just a second, she'll be with you.

21
00:04:11,822 --> 00:04:15,724
Just one second, please. You deal with this one.
I'm not going near it.

22
00:04:17,728 --> 00:04:19,696
Hello, this is the supervisor.
How can I help you?

23
00:04:21,098 --> 00:04:22,963
I can see you're on a party line...

24
00:04:23,734 --> 00:04:27,135
Unfortunately, some people do listen in
on party lines. We...

25
00:04:27,204 --> 00:04:28,831
Well, what is he doing?

26
00:04:32,143 --> 00:04:33,132
Oh, my...

27
00:04:33,210 --> 00:04:34,541
Everything all right?

28
00:04:35,613 --> 00:04:39,174
Yes, sir, it's fine.
A lady was having trouble with the connection.

29
00:04:39,450 --> 00:04:40,974
- Hey, sport.
- Hey, Mom.

30
00:04:41,051 --> 00:04:42,450
How was school?

31
00:04:42,520 --> 00:04:43,748
- Okay.
- Yeah?

32
00:04:43,821 --> 00:04:45,789
We learned about dinosaurs.

33
00:04:45,856 --> 00:04:48,154
And I got in a fight with Billy Mankowski.

34
00:04:48,225 --> 00:04:49,283
What happened?

35
00:04:49,360 --> 00:04:50,486
He hit me.

36
00:04:50,561 --> 00:04:52,085
Did you hit him back?

37
00:04:52,163 --> 00:04:53,460
Good.

38
00:04:53,531 --> 00:04:54,793
Rule number one, remember?

39
00:04:54,865 --> 00:04:57,561
Never start a fight, always finish it.

40
00:04:58,235 --> 00:04:59,793
Why'd he hit you?

41
00:04:59,870 --> 00:05:01,167
Because I hit him.

42
00:05:02,006 --> 00:05:03,530
You hit him first?

43
00:05:04,041 --> 00:05:05,065
Why?

44
00:05:06,310 --> 00:05:09,711
He said my dad ran off
because he didn't like me.

45
00:05:09,780 --> 00:05:12,146
Honey, your father never met you,

46
00:05:12,216 --> 00:05:14,150
so how could he not like you?

47
00:05:14,218 --> 00:05:16,015
Then why did he leave?

48
00:05:17,588 --> 00:05:21,046
Well, because the day you were born,

49
00:05:21,625 --> 00:05:23,525
something else arrived in the mail.

50
00:05:23,928 --> 00:05:25,520
And it was in a box
a little bit bigger than you.

51
00:05:25,596 --> 00:05:27,223
You know what was in it?

52
00:05:27,298 --> 00:05:29,061
Something called responsibility.

53
00:05:29,600 --> 00:05:31,124
And to some people,

54
00:05:31,202 --> 00:05:33,966
responsibility is the scariest thing
in the world.

55
00:05:35,239 --> 00:05:39,403
So, he ran away because he was scared
of what was in that box?

56
00:05:39,477 --> 00:05:40,501
Uh-huh.

57
00:05:40,578 --> 00:05:41,909
That's just dumb.

58
00:05:41,979 --> 00:05:43,742
That is exactly what I thought.

59
00:05:55,526 --> 00:05:57,892
Did I miss Amos 'N Andy?

60
00:05:57,962 --> 00:05:59,862
I'm afraid so, sport.

61
00:06:00,397 --> 00:06:01,796
Come now, time for bed.

62
00:06:07,271 --> 00:06:09,535
Are we still going to the movies tomorrow?

63
00:06:09,607 --> 00:06:12,872
Uh-huh. I hear there's a new
Charlie Chaplin picture

64
00:06:12,943 --> 00:06:15,741
and a new serial called
The Mysterious Airman.

65
00:06:16,013 --> 00:06:17,207
Who's that?

66
00:06:17,281 --> 00:06:19,249
I don't know. Nobody does.

67
00:06:19,316 --> 00:06:21,477
That's what makes him so mysterious.

68
00:06:21,552 --> 00:06:22,541
Oh.

69
00:06:22,920 --> 00:06:25,047
Am I too heavy for you to carry?

70
00:06:25,122 --> 00:06:27,784
Oh, no, not for years.

71
00:06:27,858 --> 00:06:29,348
Not for years.

72
00:06:37,801 --> 00:06:39,393
<i>- Hello?
- This is Margaret.</i>

73
00:06:39,470 --> 00:06:40,630
Hi, Margaret.

74
00:06:40,704 --> 00:06:41,693
<i>So, how are you?</i>

75
00:06:41,772 --> 00:06:43,000
Fine.

76
00:06:43,073 --> 00:06:45,337
<i>Listen, Jean can't come in today
and now we're a little shorthanded.</i>

77
00:06:45,409 --> 00:06:46,637
When did she call in sick?

78
00:06:46,710 --> 00:06:47,768
<i>About half hour ago.</i>

79
00:06:47,845 --> 00:06:49,506
<i>I'm having a hard time trying to find someone.</i>

80
00:06:49,580 --> 00:06:51,309
Well, what about Myrna?

81
00:06:51,382 --> 00:06:52,747
I know she could use the extra hours and...

82
00:06:52,816 --> 00:06:54,909
<i>She's busy. Can't you come?</i>

83
00:06:55,085 --> 00:06:57,747
No. No, no, no.
I just...

84
00:06:59,690 --> 00:07:03,456
I promised Walter that I'd take him to the movies,
is all, and...

85
00:07:03,527 --> 00:07:04,926
<i>Well, it's just until 4:00.</i>

86
00:07:04,995 --> 00:07:06,189
All right.

87
00:07:06,263 --> 00:07:08,060
Just...
Just until 4:00.

88
00:07:08,799 --> 00:07:10,130
I'll see you then.

89
00:07:16,307 --> 00:07:18,298
There's a sandwich and milk in the fridge,

90
00:07:18,375 --> 00:07:19,899
and I've asked Mrs. Riley and her daughter

91
00:07:19,977 --> 00:07:21,740
to stop in in a couple of hours.

92
00:07:21,812 --> 00:07:23,973
I can take care of myself.

93
00:07:24,048 --> 00:07:26,676
I know you can.
They're checking on the house, not you.

94
00:07:34,959 --> 00:07:37,655
Tomorrow we will go to the movies.

95
00:07:38,262 --> 00:07:42,699
And then we'll ride Big Red to Santa Monica
and take a walk on the pier.

96
00:07:42,766 --> 00:07:44,996
How does that sound?
Does that sound good?

97
00:07:48,606 --> 00:07:50,369
I'll be home before it gets dark.

98
00:07:50,674 --> 00:07:52,335
I'm not afraid of the dark.

99
00:07:52,409 --> 00:07:54,206
I'm not afraid of anything.

100
00:07:55,079 --> 00:07:57,843
I know. I know.

101
00:08:00,417 --> 00:08:01,975
Be good.

102
00:08:02,152 --> 00:08:03,710
I love you.

103
00:08:39,056 --> 00:08:41,524
We've got lines jammed from here to Ohio.

104
00:08:41,592 --> 00:08:44,026
He says he needs to speak
to somebody in charge.

105
00:08:44,662 --> 00:08:47,756
I need your signature here
for a supply requisition.

106
00:08:47,831 --> 00:08:49,856
- Number, please.
- Number, please.

107
00:08:50,768 --> 00:08:52,201
Go ahead, please.

108
00:08:54,038 --> 00:08:56,268
All right, get me the Omaha routing station.

109
00:08:56,340 --> 00:08:58,740
See if we can put our calls
through their switchers.

110
00:08:58,809 --> 00:09:00,401
Let's get this console running, now.

111
00:09:04,715 --> 00:09:08,048
Christine.
Good, I was hoping to catch you.

112
00:09:08,452 --> 00:09:10,511
Look, I've been following your work reports,

113
00:09:10,587 --> 00:09:12,782
and I just want to let you know
that I am very impressed.

114
00:09:12,856 --> 00:09:15,290
When I first suggested
hiring female supervisors,

115
00:09:15,359 --> 00:09:16,917
my superiors weren't big on the idea.

116
00:09:16,994 --> 00:09:19,861
But you have held your own as well
as any of your male counterparts.

117
00:09:19,930 --> 00:09:20,954
Thank you, Mr. Harris.

118
00:09:21,031 --> 00:09:22,555
Oh, Ben, please.
Listen, I...

119
00:09:22,633 --> 00:09:23,725
Listen, the point is,

120
00:09:23,801 --> 00:09:26,599
we're looking to take on a manager
for our new Beverly Hills office.

121
00:09:26,670 --> 00:09:29,696
And if you're interested in the job,
I could write a report, or...

122
00:09:29,773 --> 00:09:31,570
That would be wonderful.
Thank you so much, sir.

123
00:09:31,642 --> 00:09:33,906
Okay, good, so maybe we could...

124
00:09:33,977 --> 00:09:35,444
- Could we speak about it Monday?
- Yeah, absolutely.

125
00:09:35,512 --> 00:09:38,003
Would that be all right?
Thank you so much, sir. Thank you.

126
00:09:46,123 --> 00:09:47,385
Please!

127
00:09:50,027 --> 00:09:51,289
Please.

128
00:10:23,060 --> 00:10:24,391
Walter.

129
00:10:26,296 --> 00:10:27,490
Honey?

130
00:10:29,433 --> 00:10:30,832
Walter.

131
00:10:31,168 --> 00:10:32,396
Walter!

132
00:10:33,470 --> 00:10:34,767
Honey?

133
00:10:50,154 --> 00:10:51,348
Walter?

134
00:10:57,795 --> 00:10:58,989
Honey!

135
00:11:02,099 --> 00:11:03,430
Walter!

136
00:11:04,468 --> 00:11:07,062
Walter, it's time to come in, honey.

137
00:11:10,307 --> 00:11:12,832
Suzie?
Have you seen Walter?

138
00:11:14,711 --> 00:11:15,803
No, Mrs. Collins.

139
00:11:15,879 --> 00:11:17,073
Sorry.

140
00:11:26,790 --> 00:11:27,882
Walter?

141
00:11:31,261 --> 00:11:32,626
Walter.

142
00:11:56,787 --> 00:11:58,015
<i>Number, please.</i>

143
00:11:58,088 --> 00:12:00,113
May I please have the police station?

144
00:12:00,190 --> 00:12:01,714
<i>I'll connect you.</i>

145
00:12:01,792 --> 00:12:02,781
<i>Lincoln Heights Division.</i>

146
00:12:02,860 --> 00:12:04,657
Hello, my name is Christine Collins.

147
00:12:04,728 --> 00:12:07,253
I live at 210 North Avenue, 23.

148
00:12:07,764 --> 00:12:10,232
And I'm calling to report a missing child.

149
00:12:10,300 --> 00:12:11,767
Missing child.

150
00:12:11,835 --> 00:12:14,895
<i>What's your relation to the child, ma'am?</i>

151
00:12:14,972 --> 00:12:16,371
It's my son.

152
00:12:16,506 --> 00:12:18,667
<i>How long has he been gone?</i>

153
00:12:19,076 --> 00:12:21,135
I'm not sure.
I just got home from work.

154
00:12:22,446 --> 00:12:24,641
It could be since this morning

155
00:12:24,715 --> 00:12:26,444
or it could be just the last hour.

156
00:12:26,516 --> 00:12:27,574
<i>Have you checked around the neighborhood?</i>

157
00:12:27,651 --> 00:12:29,380
Yes, of course I did.

158
00:12:29,453 --> 00:12:31,512
<i>Well, maybe he's lost track of time.</i>

159
00:12:31,588 --> 00:12:32,850
No. No, no.

160
00:12:32,923 --> 00:12:36,359
He always stays around the house
when it gets dark.

161
00:12:36,426 --> 00:12:38,485
Would you please send someone down here?

162
00:12:38,595 --> 00:12:39,960
<i>I'm sorry, but our policy is that</i>

163
00:12:40,030 --> 00:12:43,989
<i>we don't dispatch units
on missing child cases for 24 hours.</i>

164
00:12:45,235 --> 00:12:46,327
What?

165
00:12:46,403 --> 00:12:49,861
<i>Look, 99 times out of 100,
the kid shows up by morning.</i>

166
00:12:49,973 --> 00:12:53,841
<i>We don't have the resources to go chasing every kid
who runs off with his pals.</i>

167
00:12:53,911 --> 00:12:55,003
No, no, no.

168
00:12:55,078 --> 00:12:57,706
No, that's not Walter.
He doesn't do that.

169
00:12:57,781 --> 00:13:02,115
<i>With all due respect, ma'am,
every parent who calls says the same thing.</i>

170
00:13:03,153 --> 00:13:05,212
Please, please.

171
00:13:05,289 --> 00:13:06,950
<i>Look, there's nothing I can do.</i>

172
00:13:07,024 --> 00:13:08,491
<i>I'll take your name and your information,</i>

173
00:13:08,558 --> 00:13:11,186
<i>but that's all until the morning,
at the earliest.</i>

174
00:13:11,261 --> 00:13:14,287
<i>I'm sure he'll show up by then.
They always do.</i>

175
00:13:42,759 --> 00:13:44,454
Are you Mrs. Collins?

176
00:13:59,209 --> 00:14:03,737
<i>Our thoughts go out again today
to Mrs. Christine Collins</i>

177
00:14:03,814 --> 00:14:05,247
<i>of Lincoln Heights,</i>

178
00:14:05,315 --> 00:14:07,476
<i>whose young son, Walter Collins,</i>

179
00:14:07,551 --> 00:14:10,076
<i>disappeared nearly two weeks ago.</i>

180
00:14:11,154 --> 00:14:14,612
<i>Though she is not
a member of our congregation,</i>

181
00:14:14,858 --> 00:14:18,419
<i>we pray for her today
as we have every day,</i>

182
00:14:19,329 --> 00:14:21,729
<i>since we learned of her plight.</i>

183
00:14:22,332 --> 00:14:24,664
<i>On the radio and in the newspapers</i>

184
00:14:24,735 --> 00:14:27,670
<i>we are told that
the Los Angeles Police Department</i>

185
00:14:27,738 --> 00:14:32,334
<i>is doing its very best
to reunite mother and child,</i>

186
00:14:32,409 --> 00:14:34,809
<i>and I'm sure that that is true.</i>

187
00:14:36,346 --> 00:14:40,976
<i>But given its status
as the most violent, corrupt</i>

188
00:14:41,051 --> 00:14:43,019
<i>and incompetent police department</i>

189
00:14:43,086 --> 00:14:45,316
<i>this side of the Rocky Mountains</i>

190
00:14:45,389 --> 00:14:48,847
<i>I am not sure it's saying a great deal.</i>

191
00:14:56,533 --> 00:14:59,832
<i>Every day, new bodies appear along Mulholland</i>

192
00:14:59,903 --> 00:15:01,928
<i>and in the ditches of our cities,</i>

193
00:15:02,005 --> 00:15:08,410
<i>the work of Police Chief James Davis
and his aptly named Gun Squad.</i>

194
00:15:08,478 --> 00:15:11,845
<i>Every day, the needs of honest citizens</i>

195
00:15:11,915 --> 00:15:16,147
<i>are put second to greed and personal gain.</i>

196
00:15:16,753 --> 00:15:22,714
<i>Every day, this city sinks deeper
into a cesspool of fear,</i>

197
00:15:22,793 --> 00:15:27,594
<i>intimidation and corruption.</i>

198
00:15:27,664 --> 00:15:30,064
<i>Once the City of Angels,</i>

199
00:15:30,133 --> 00:15:35,196
<i>Los Angeles has become
a place where our protectors</i>

200
00:15:35,272 --> 00:15:37,763
<i>have become our brutalizers.</i>

201
00:15:38,141 --> 00:15:42,805
<i>Where to be the law is
to be above the law.</i>

202
00:16:30,627 --> 00:16:32,185
I understand.
Thank you.

203
00:16:32,262 --> 00:16:34,059
I will call back in a few weeks.

204
00:16:34,564 --> 00:16:36,395
Thank you very much.

205
00:16:39,636 --> 00:16:41,968
Las Vegas Missing Persons Department?

206
00:16:42,506 --> 00:16:44,269
Hello, this is Christine Collins.

207
00:16:44,341 --> 00:16:47,208
I'm calling to see if you've found
any missing or lost children

208
00:16:47,277 --> 00:16:51,145
who meet the description
that matches Walter Collins.

209
00:16:53,116 --> 00:16:56,051
Oh, all right.
Well, please do. Please do call.

210
00:16:56,119 --> 00:16:57,677
And I'll call back in a matter...

211
00:16:57,754 --> 00:17:00,518
In a week, if that's all right.
Thank you very much.

212
00:17:00,590 --> 00:17:01,579
Thank you.

213
00:17:17,274 --> 00:17:18,502
$2.

214
00:17:28,185 --> 00:17:30,483
Hell, I think I left my wallet at home.

215
00:17:30,987 --> 00:17:32,454
Can I owe it to you?

216
00:17:33,290 --> 00:17:34,951
No credit.

217
00:17:35,025 --> 00:17:36,686
Pay up or I call the cops.

218
00:17:36,760 --> 00:17:38,591
I'm sick of bums like you
coming around here.

219
00:17:38,662 --> 00:17:40,095
I'm not trying to stiff you, chief.

220
00:17:40,163 --> 00:17:42,654
I just left my wallet at home, that's all.

221
00:17:42,732 --> 00:17:45,701
I'll go back and get it.
Five, 10 minutes, tops.

222
00:17:49,005 --> 00:17:50,666
Got collateral?

223
00:17:51,107 --> 00:17:52,506
You can't ask for better collateral

224
00:17:52,576 --> 00:17:54,874
than a man's own flesh and blood, right?

225
00:17:55,912 --> 00:17:57,470
Now, you stay here, son.

226
00:17:57,714 --> 00:17:59,079
I'll be right back.

227
00:17:59,149 --> 00:18:01,674
- But...
- Now, don't give me any trouble.

228
00:18:01,751 --> 00:18:03,742
He's a good man to trust us like this.

229
00:18:04,554 --> 00:18:08,388
Now, you just stay here
and I'll go back and get my wallet.

230
00:18:11,661 --> 00:18:14,095
Ten minutes, then I call the cops.

231
00:18:24,274 --> 00:18:25,764
Ah, hell.

232
00:18:30,814 --> 00:18:32,338
<i>- Number, please.
- Hello, Myrtle?</i>

233
00:18:32,415 --> 00:18:34,280
<i>- Hello?
- Yeah, this is Harve, down at the diner.</i>

234
00:18:34,351 --> 00:18:35,409
<i>Oh, hi, Harve.</i>

235
00:18:35,485 --> 00:18:36,645
Would you get me Sheriff Larsen?

236
00:18:36,720 --> 00:18:37,618
<i>Sure thing.</i>

237
00:18:39,422 --> 00:18:41,151
You have a nice day, too.

238
00:18:44,494 --> 00:18:46,655
Christine, I'm having trouble
with the connection here.

239
00:18:46,730 --> 00:18:48,595
I can't seem to get through.

240
00:18:48,665 --> 00:18:51,065
I think so.
Yeah, I think that's better.

241
00:18:54,471 --> 00:18:57,440
You have a person to person call,
Fairfax 2231.

242
00:18:57,507 --> 00:18:59,998
Long distance.
Sorry, can you repeat?

243
00:19:00,076 --> 00:19:01,839
I'll connect you right away, ma'am.

244
00:19:02,012 --> 00:19:03,274
Thanks.

245
00:19:16,860 --> 00:19:18,191
Mrs. Collins?

246
00:19:18,561 --> 00:19:19,585
Yes.

247
00:19:20,463 --> 00:19:23,364
I'm Captain J.J. Jones,
Lincoln Park Juvenile Division.

248
00:19:24,334 --> 00:19:27,963
My office supervises
all runaway and missing child cases,

249
00:19:28,038 --> 00:19:29,903
including your son's, and...

250
00:19:30,707 --> 00:19:32,572
He's alive, Mrs. Collins.

251
00:19:36,479 --> 00:19:39,380
He was picked up two days ago
by local police in DeKalb, Illinois.

252
00:19:39,449 --> 00:19:40,882
He's safe and unhurt.

253
00:19:43,787 --> 00:19:46,381
He was in the company of some drifter.
We have an APB out for him,

254
00:19:46,456 --> 00:19:47,480
but he's safe.

255
00:19:48,591 --> 00:19:51,492
Thank you so much.

256
00:19:52,095 --> 00:19:53,756
Oh, Christine...

257
00:19:55,765 --> 00:19:57,062
That is so great.

258
00:20:05,008 --> 00:20:06,100
Thank you.

259
00:20:23,159 --> 00:20:24,751
There's so much press.

260
00:20:25,428 --> 00:20:27,828
Yours is a story with a happy ending,
Mrs. Collins.

261
00:20:27,897 --> 00:20:30,092
People love happy endings.

262
00:20:30,834 --> 00:20:33,530
We better get a move on,
the train's pulling in.

263
00:20:35,105 --> 00:20:37,039
Back, boys. Back.

264
00:20:37,340 --> 00:20:39,171
Thanks.
Thanks, boys, thanks!

265
00:20:39,242 --> 00:20:40,732
I'll have a statement for you
in a few minutes,

266
00:20:40,810 --> 00:20:41,868
but the important thing right now

267
00:20:41,945 --> 00:20:43,708
is to reunite this little lady with her son,

268
00:20:43,780 --> 00:20:45,145
so if you'll excuse us.

269
00:20:48,718 --> 00:20:50,413
Stay right there.
Come on, don't rush.

270
00:20:51,321 --> 00:20:52,583
Easy, easy.

271
00:20:54,524 --> 00:20:57,049
Mrs. Collins, I'd like to introduce you
to James E. Davis,

272
00:20:57,127 --> 00:20:58,321
Chief of Police.

273
00:20:58,395 --> 00:20:59,384
Very nice to meet you.

274
00:20:59,462 --> 00:21:00,827
We don't get a lot of positive attention

275
00:21:00,897 --> 00:21:02,387
from the boys in the press these days,

276
00:21:02,465 --> 00:21:04,956
so it's good to be here with a positive story,
don't you think?

277
00:21:05,034 --> 00:21:06,092
Yes, sir.

278
00:21:06,169 --> 00:21:10,538
I take it you've been treated well
by my boys in the department?

279
00:21:10,607 --> 00:21:12,700
I couldn't file a report for 24 hours,

280
00:21:12,776 --> 00:21:14,038
and I thought that maybe that was a...

281
00:21:14,110 --> 00:21:15,543
Technicalities aside.

282
00:21:17,580 --> 00:21:18,740
It was wonderful.

283
00:21:18,815 --> 00:21:19,941
Well, good.

284
00:21:21,985 --> 00:21:23,885
Then you won't have any trouble telling that
to the press,

285
00:21:23,953 --> 00:21:25,887
and the fact that the LAPD...

286
00:21:29,159 --> 00:21:30,251
Women.

287
00:21:30,326 --> 00:21:31,486
Hold on a second.

288
00:21:39,602 --> 00:21:41,160
Back, boys, back.

289
00:21:43,173 --> 00:21:44,401
Keep them back.

290
00:22:03,893 --> 00:22:06,885
Well, aren't you...
Aren't you gonna...

291
00:22:06,963 --> 00:22:08,225
That's not my son.

292
00:22:11,501 --> 00:22:12,661
What?

293
00:22:13,903 --> 00:22:15,234
What are you saying?

294
00:22:15,505 --> 00:22:17,302
It's not my son.

295
00:22:17,373 --> 00:22:19,739
Well, I'm sure you're mistaken.

296
00:22:19,809 --> 00:22:20,901
I'm not mistaken.

297
00:22:20,977 --> 00:22:23,605
Well, he's been through
five terrible long months.

298
00:22:23,680 --> 00:22:25,807
He's lost weight, he's changed.

299
00:22:25,882 --> 00:22:27,577
I would know my own son.

300
00:22:27,650 --> 00:22:30,448
All I'm saying is you're in shock
and he's changed.

301
00:22:32,288 --> 00:22:33,983
What's your name?
Can you tell me your name?

302
00:22:34,057 --> 00:22:35,684
Walter Collins.

303
00:22:37,927 --> 00:22:39,417
It's a common name.

304
00:22:39,496 --> 00:22:41,657
Where do you live, Walter?
You know your home address?

305
00:22:41,731 --> 00:22:44,962
I live at 210 Avenue 23,

306
00:22:45,301 --> 00:22:47,292
Los Angeles, California.

307
00:22:47,370 --> 00:22:49,270
And that's my mommy!

308
00:22:54,043 --> 00:22:57,410
Mrs. Collins, listen to me.
I understand.

309
00:22:57,480 --> 00:23:00,472
You're feeling a little uncertain right now,
and that's to be expected.

310
00:23:00,550 --> 00:23:02,916
A boy this age, he changes so fast.

311
00:23:03,453 --> 00:23:05,921
We've compensated for that in our investigation.

312
00:23:05,989 --> 00:23:08,958
And there's no question
that this is your son.

313
00:23:09,025 --> 00:23:11,050
That is not Walter.

314
00:23:13,263 --> 00:23:15,231
It's not Walter as you remember him.

315
00:23:15,732 --> 00:23:19,930
And that's why it's important for you
to take him home on a trial basis.

316
00:23:21,371 --> 00:23:22,895
A trial basis?

317
00:23:22,972 --> 00:23:24,030
Yes, yes.

318
00:23:24,107 --> 00:23:27,634
Once he's around his familiar surroundings,

319
00:23:27,710 --> 00:23:31,646
and you've given yourself time to recover
from the shock of his changed condition,

320
00:23:31,714 --> 00:23:34,478
you will see that this is your Walter.

321
00:23:34,551 --> 00:23:37,111
Now, I promise you, I swear to you,
I give you my word.

322
00:23:37,186 --> 00:23:38,813
This is your son.

323
00:23:38,888 --> 00:23:42,449
Now, if you have any problems, any problems at all,
you come and you talk to me.

324
00:23:42,525 --> 00:23:43,856
I'll take care of it.

325
00:23:45,528 --> 00:23:47,860
I give you my word.
Trust me.

326
00:23:48,431 --> 00:23:51,923
Mrs. Collins, he has nowhere else to go.

327
00:23:55,672 --> 00:23:56,900
Please.

328
00:24:01,511 --> 00:24:04,036
Maybe I'm not thinking clearly.

329
00:24:04,113 --> 00:24:05,944
And...

330
00:24:07,383 --> 00:24:08,543
All right.

331
00:24:08,618 --> 00:24:11,143
All right, you're not thinking clearly,
that's right.

332
00:24:11,220 --> 00:24:12,653
Here we go!

333
00:24:13,156 --> 00:24:14,487
Thank you.
Thank you.

334
00:24:14,557 --> 00:24:16,616
Here, just turn around here.

335
00:24:17,060 --> 00:24:18,755
How does it feel to have your son home,
Mrs. Collins?

336
00:24:18,828 --> 00:24:20,819
What'd you think when you saw him
for the first time?

337
00:24:20,897 --> 00:24:23,195
It's hard to explain.

338
00:24:23,266 --> 00:24:25,097
She was shocked at first.

339
00:24:25,168 --> 00:24:28,137
She didn't recognize the boy,
which is perfectly natural.

340
00:24:28,204 --> 00:24:29,569
He's been through quite an ordeal.

341
00:24:29,639 --> 00:24:31,106
How're you feeling, son?

342
00:24:31,174 --> 00:24:32,232
Bet it feels great to be home.

343
00:24:32,308 --> 00:24:33,605
Yeah. It's great.

344
00:24:33,676 --> 00:24:35,837
The Los Angeles Police Department is thankful

345
00:24:35,912 --> 00:24:39,109
for all the hard work done
by the DeKalb County Sheriff's Department

346
00:24:39,182 --> 00:24:41,810
in making this joyful reunion possible.

347
00:24:41,884 --> 00:24:44,580
The LAPD is dedicated to serving the public
at all times.

348
00:24:44,654 --> 00:24:47,282
Can we get a photo with mother and son, Captain?

349
00:24:47,357 --> 00:24:49,552
Absolutely! Here we are.

350
00:24:49,759 --> 00:24:51,386
Like that.
Like that.

351
00:24:51,461 --> 00:24:54,021
Squeeze together.
There you go, boys.

352
00:24:54,897 --> 00:24:56,660
- This way, Walter.
- Big smile.

353
00:24:57,133 --> 00:24:58,794
- One more, please.
- That's a good one.

354
00:24:59,936 --> 00:25:01,130
One more.

355
00:25:22,725 --> 00:25:24,124
The sandwich all right?

356
00:25:26,763 --> 00:25:28,128
Would you like some more milk?

357
00:25:28,197 --> 00:25:29,323
No.

358
00:25:30,700 --> 00:25:31,962
No, thank you.

359
00:25:32,468 --> 00:25:33,696
No, thank you.

360
00:25:40,109 --> 00:25:44,136
You're covered in soot from the train.
You should take a bath.

361
00:25:55,391 --> 00:25:58,019
Pajamas are on the edge of the bed.

362
00:26:01,064 --> 00:26:02,725
You okay?
You all right?

363
00:26:02,799 --> 00:26:04,767
I fell. Stupid tub!

364
00:26:05,501 --> 00:26:07,264
That's all right.

365
00:26:09,939 --> 00:26:11,736
You're circumcised.

366
00:26:17,180 --> 00:26:18,511
Get out.

367
00:26:19,849 --> 00:26:21,043
Move.

368
00:26:31,994 --> 00:26:34,053
Last time I measured Walter,

369
00:26:34,130 --> 00:26:36,394
last time I measured my son,

370
00:26:36,466 --> 00:26:38,525
he was inches taller
than you are now.

371
00:26:39,469 --> 00:26:40,902
Who are you?

372
00:26:42,071 --> 00:26:44,130
What are you doing here?

373
00:26:45,274 --> 00:26:46,764
Who are you?

374
00:26:48,044 --> 00:26:49,238
Who are you?

375
00:27:03,025 --> 00:27:03,889
He's not my son.

376
00:27:03,960 --> 00:27:05,018
Mrs. Collins...

377
00:27:05,094 --> 00:27:07,221
No, I don't know why he's saying that he is,

378
00:27:07,296 --> 00:27:09,025
but he's not Walter
and there's been a mistake.

379
00:27:09,098 --> 00:27:11,123
I thought we agreed to give him time to adjust.

380
00:27:11,200 --> 00:27:12,861
He's three inches shorter.

381
00:27:13,236 --> 00:27:14,567
I measured him on the chart.

382
00:27:14,637 --> 00:27:16,036
Well, maybe your measurements are off.

383
00:27:16,105 --> 00:27:19,040
Look, I'm sure there's a reasonable explanation
for all of this.

384
00:27:19,108 --> 00:27:20,439
He's circumcised.

385
00:27:21,077 --> 00:27:22,408
And Walter isn't.

386
00:27:23,713 --> 00:27:24,975
Mrs. Collins.

387
00:27:28,785 --> 00:27:30,616
Your son was missing for five months.

388
00:27:30,686 --> 00:27:35,248
For at least part of that time in the company
of an as yet unidentified drifter.

389
00:27:35,324 --> 00:27:38,157
Who knows what such a disturbed individual
might have done?

390
00:27:38,928 --> 00:27:42,022
He could have had him circumcised.
He could have...

391
00:27:42,098 --> 00:27:43,565
Made him shorter?

392
00:27:48,504 --> 00:27:49,869
Why aren't you listening to me?

393
00:27:49,939 --> 00:27:52,931
I am listening, damn it,
I am listening.

394
00:27:53,009 --> 00:27:54,533
And I understand your feelings.

395
00:27:54,610 --> 00:27:56,737
He's changed, no mistake,
and that's...

396
00:27:56,813 --> 00:27:58,440
You've both been through
a terrible experience,

397
00:27:58,514 --> 00:28:01,415
and that's why he needs
your love and support to bounce back.

398
00:28:01,517 --> 00:28:03,007
He's not my son!

399
00:28:04,153 --> 00:28:06,280
Why are you doing this, Mrs. Collins?

400
00:28:06,355 --> 00:28:07,447
Why are you doing this?

401
00:28:07,523 --> 00:28:10,583
You seem perfectly capable
of taking care of the boy.

402
00:28:10,660 --> 00:28:13,060
Your job pays you enough
to attend to his personal needs,

403
00:28:13,129 --> 00:28:14,858
so I don't understand
why you're running away

404
00:28:14,931 --> 00:28:16,728
from your responsibilities as a mother.

405
00:28:16,799 --> 00:28:19,063
I am not running away from anything!

406
00:28:19,135 --> 00:28:20,602
Least of all my responsibilities!

407
00:28:20,670 --> 00:28:23,264
I am even taking care of that boy right now,

408
00:28:23,339 --> 00:28:25,170
because I am all he has!

409
00:28:25,241 --> 00:28:27,539
What worries me is that you have stopped
looking for my son!

410
00:28:27,610 --> 00:28:32,104
Why should we be looking for someone
we've already found?

411
00:28:32,515 --> 00:28:35,609
Because you have not found him.

412
00:28:35,685 --> 00:28:38,119
His identity has been confirmed

413
00:28:38,187 --> 00:28:41,679
by the best minds
in the field of child identification,

414
00:28:42,124 --> 00:28:43,955
people who know what they're doing.

415
00:28:44,026 --> 00:28:45,425
And I don't?

416
00:29:03,045 --> 00:29:05,878
I'm sorry.

417
00:29:06,849 --> 00:29:08,874
I appreciate everything
that this department has done

418
00:29:08,951 --> 00:29:11,078
and I know how hard you're working.

419
00:29:11,153 --> 00:29:14,247
I really do,
and I don't want to cause any trouble.

420
00:29:14,323 --> 00:29:17,087
I just...
There has been a terrible mistake,

421
00:29:17,159 --> 00:29:19,320
and I need you to help me correct it,

422
00:29:19,395 --> 00:29:24,230
so I can find my son before it's too late.

423
00:29:26,502 --> 00:29:27,628
Please.

424
00:29:36,679 --> 00:29:40,342
I won't take up any more of your time.
I'm sorry I got upset.

425
00:29:40,416 --> 00:29:42,350
I'm sorry, very sorry.

426
00:29:55,031 --> 00:29:56,020
<i>Yes, Captain?</i>

427
00:29:56,098 --> 00:29:58,089
Sara, get Dr. Tarr on the phone.

428
00:29:58,167 --> 00:29:59,293
<i>Yes, sir.</i>

429
00:30:04,607 --> 00:30:05,631
- Mrs. Collins?
- Yes?

430
00:30:05,708 --> 00:30:07,335
Dr. Earl W. Tarr.

431
00:30:07,410 --> 00:30:08,434
Captain Jones sent me.

432
00:30:08,511 --> 00:30:10,945
I consult with him from time to time
on juvenile cases.

433
00:30:11,013 --> 00:30:12,378
May I come in?

434
00:30:12,682 --> 00:30:14,616
Yes, thank you for coming.

435
00:30:14,684 --> 00:30:16,481
I was beginning to think he didn't believe me.

436
00:30:16,552 --> 00:30:19,919
Well, I'm here now,
and we'll put all that to rights.

437
00:30:21,190 --> 00:30:22,748
Where's the boy?

438
00:30:25,528 --> 00:30:27,519
Ah! There he is.

439
00:30:28,864 --> 00:30:30,525
A handsome young man.

440
00:30:31,233 --> 00:30:33,064
He has your eyes, doesn't he?

441
00:30:33,135 --> 00:30:35,365
And a little bit of the nose.

442
00:30:35,638 --> 00:30:38,766
Very fit, in spite of all his travails.

443
00:30:38,841 --> 00:30:42,140
A very resilient boy you've got here,
Mrs. Collins.

444
00:30:43,112 --> 00:30:44,773
I thought you were here to help me.

445
00:30:44,847 --> 00:30:46,337
Well, I am.

446
00:30:46,415 --> 00:30:49,851
Captain Jones said that the boy
had been through some severe physical changes

447
00:30:49,919 --> 00:30:51,443
and asked me to drop in on him,

448
00:30:51,520 --> 00:30:54,114
to reassure you in your time
of motherly concern.

449
00:30:55,124 --> 00:30:59,584
My motherly concern is not for him
because he's not my son.

450
00:31:00,296 --> 00:31:04,824
Now, statements like that will hardly help
the boy's self-esteem,

451
00:31:04,900 --> 00:31:06,299
now will they?

452
00:31:07,570 --> 00:31:10,300
Captain Jones said something
about a change in height?

453
00:31:11,173 --> 00:31:12,231
Yes.

454
00:31:13,342 --> 00:31:14,673
Come.

455
00:31:16,812 --> 00:31:18,143
Against the wall.

456
00:31:22,018 --> 00:31:23,542
He's three inches shorter.

457
00:31:24,320 --> 00:31:26,083
Ah, well...

458
00:31:27,056 --> 00:31:30,685
Hardly a mystery, Mrs. Collins.

459
00:31:30,760 --> 00:31:35,060
We've known for some time that trauma
can affect the growth of children.

460
00:31:35,131 --> 00:31:37,292
Given the stress of the past five months,

461
00:31:37,733 --> 00:31:39,826
his spine may have actually shrunk.

462
00:31:39,902 --> 00:31:42,871
It's uncommon, but it's within
the realm of possibility.

463
00:31:45,541 --> 00:31:46,906
And circumcision?

464
00:31:50,546 --> 00:31:54,175
Very likely his abductor thought it appropriate.

465
00:31:54,250 --> 00:31:57,014
After all, circumcision is hygienically sound.

466
00:31:58,421 --> 00:32:01,390
Must have been quite traumatic at the time.

467
00:32:02,758 --> 00:32:05,420
No wonder he's submerged the memory.

468
00:32:07,863 --> 00:32:08,887
I...

469
00:32:08,964 --> 00:32:13,298
You see, there's a perfectly sound
medical explanation for all of this.

470
00:32:14,470 --> 00:32:16,734
But it's right for you to raise the questions.

471
00:32:16,806 --> 00:32:19,832
You need to be apprised of all changes
the lad went through

472
00:32:19,909 --> 00:32:21,968
during his absence.

473
00:32:22,044 --> 00:32:25,309
Wouldn't I know whether or not he's my son?

474
00:32:26,248 --> 00:32:27,772
I'm the mother.

475
00:32:28,317 --> 00:32:30,808
Which means you're in no position to be objective.

476
00:32:31,687 --> 00:32:35,783
You are looking through the prism
of extreme emotion at a boy

477
00:32:36,158 --> 00:32:38,456
who has changed from what you remember.

478
00:32:38,527 --> 00:32:40,552
He isn't the same boy that left here.

479
00:32:40,629 --> 00:32:42,756
Just as a boy that goes off to war
and then returns

480
00:32:42,832 --> 00:32:44,663
is not the same anymore.

481
00:32:44,733 --> 00:32:49,397
And a mother's heart,
driven by intuition and emotion,

482
00:32:49,472 --> 00:32:51,906
sees these changes and rebels,

483
00:32:52,608 --> 00:32:54,940
insists that this isn't your son.

484
00:32:56,612 --> 00:32:58,341
Doesn't change the facts.

485
00:33:02,151 --> 00:33:06,417
I'm willing to put my theory
to the test of objectivity, Mrs. Collins.

486
00:33:07,256 --> 00:33:08,621
Are you?

487
00:33:15,898 --> 00:33:18,025
<i>It is absolutely outrageous!</i>

488
00:33:18,100 --> 00:33:21,001
Calm yourself, calm yourself
and just listen to me.

489
00:33:21,070 --> 00:33:25,131
No, no, no.
No, you listen to me, please.

490
00:33:25,808 --> 00:33:29,676
This so called doctor paraded me around
my own neighborhood,

491
00:33:29,745 --> 00:33:33,078
like some kind of a derelict mother
who didn't even know her own son.

492
00:33:33,149 --> 00:33:35,140
<i>And what was his findings?</i>

493
00:33:35,217 --> 00:33:37,481
He found what he expected to find,

494
00:33:38,254 --> 00:33:41,155
what you obviously told him he would find.

495
00:33:41,223 --> 00:33:42,690
<i>- Mrs. Collins.
- But that's not...</i>

496
00:33:42,758 --> 00:33:44,419
That's nothing to be embarrassed about.

497
00:33:44,493 --> 00:33:48,987
That I was embarrassed is not the issue.

498
00:33:51,133 --> 00:33:54,102
The point is that you are wasting time

499
00:33:54,170 --> 00:33:57,333
when you should be looking for my son.

500
00:33:57,406 --> 00:34:00,466
But the report is final, Mrs. Collins.

501
00:34:01,443 --> 00:34:04,640
Well, then I want to receive the report,
so I can refute it,

502
00:34:04,713 --> 00:34:06,647
before it goes to anyone else.

503
00:34:06,715 --> 00:34:07,943
Fine.

504
00:34:08,851 --> 00:34:11,115
Yes. Good day.

505
00:34:19,528 --> 00:34:21,894
I'm finished.
Could I go to my room now?

506
00:34:23,832 --> 00:34:24,992
Yes.

507
00:34:34,543 --> 00:34:36,204
Good night, Mommy.

508
00:34:37,646 --> 00:34:39,944
Stop saying that!

509
00:34:41,383 --> 00:34:43,476
Stop saying that!

510
00:34:43,752 --> 00:34:45,652
I'm not your mother!

511
00:34:48,691 --> 00:34:51,285
I want my son back.

512
00:34:51,360 --> 00:34:54,989
You're not him.
You're not my son!

513
00:34:57,967 --> 00:35:00,060
I want my son back.

514
00:35:00,970 --> 00:35:03,495
I want my son back!

515
00:35:04,039 --> 00:35:05,404
Damn you!

516
00:35:06,475 --> 00:35:08,943
I want my son back!

517
00:35:42,144 --> 00:35:44,374
I was wrong to yell at you.

518
00:35:47,516 --> 00:35:49,108
You're just a child,

519
00:35:50,619 --> 00:35:53,383
and I don't think you know
what you're doing,

520
00:35:53,455 --> 00:35:55,446
and the hurt you're causing.

521
00:35:55,524 --> 00:36:00,962
But I need you to understand
that my son is my life.

522
00:36:03,065 --> 00:36:05,226
He's all I have.

523
00:36:07,369 --> 00:36:11,567
And no matter what the police think,
and no matter what the world thinks,

524
00:36:13,175 --> 00:36:14,972
you and I,

525
00:36:16,078 --> 00:36:19,070
we both know the truth,
don't we?

526
00:36:19,381 --> 00:36:23,647
We both know that you're not Walter.

527
00:36:23,719 --> 00:36:27,712
You just have to tell them
that you're not my son,

528
00:36:27,790 --> 00:36:29,758
so they can find my son.

529
00:36:33,329 --> 00:36:34,591
Please.

530
00:36:41,170 --> 00:36:44,071
We can talk tomorrow.

531
00:37:05,961 --> 00:37:07,053
Hello?

532
00:37:07,129 --> 00:37:09,154
<i>Is this Mrs. Christine Collins?</i>

533
00:37:09,231 --> 00:37:10,789
Yes.

534
00:37:10,866 --> 00:37:12,458
My name is Gustav Briegleb.

535
00:37:12,534 --> 00:37:15,901
I'm the pastor over at St. Paul's Presbyterian.

536
00:37:17,239 --> 00:37:19,207
Oh, yes, I've heard your broadcasts.

537
00:37:19,274 --> 00:37:20,798
I'm...

538
00:37:20,876 --> 00:37:22,776
Thank you.

539
00:37:22,845 --> 00:37:25,405
<i>Have you read the Times this morning?</i>

540
00:37:25,481 --> 00:37:26,607
No.

541
00:37:27,116 --> 00:37:31,314
<i>Well, maybe you should give it a gander
and then come over here to the parish for breakfast,</i>

542
00:37:31,387 --> 00:37:34,447
in, say, an hour.
I think we should meet.

543
00:37:37,126 --> 00:37:38,286
Hello?

544
00:37:46,268 --> 00:37:48,293
"Mysterious case of...

545
00:37:48,370 --> 00:37:50,736
Acting on the request of the
Los Angeles Police Department,

546
00:37:50,806 --> 00:37:54,970
Dr. Earl W. Tarr, child specialist,
examined Walter Collins

547
00:37:55,043 --> 00:37:56,840
to determine the cause of his loss of weight,

548
00:37:56,912 --> 00:37:59,574
paleness, confusion, and rundown condition

549
00:37:59,648 --> 00:38:00,842
noticed since the return of the boy

550
00:38:00,916 --> 00:38:03,407
to his mother last Monday."

551
00:38:04,987 --> 00:38:07,217
Lovely bit of phrasing, isn't it?

552
00:38:07,289 --> 00:38:10,315
Noticed since the return of the boy
to his mother.

553
00:38:10,392 --> 00:38:13,156
Now, not only does that clearly state
you're the boy's mother,

554
00:38:13,228 --> 00:38:17,597
but one could infer from it
that you're somehow responsible for these changes.

555
00:38:17,666 --> 00:38:19,964
And that the police department is concerned

556
00:38:20,035 --> 00:38:22,799
for the boy's welfare while he's in your charge.

557
00:38:22,871 --> 00:38:25,362
You should try the eggs.
They're very nice.

558
00:38:26,041 --> 00:38:29,636
"'I examined the boy quite thoroughly',
Dr. Tarr said,

559
00:38:29,711 --> 00:38:32,179
'And it's clear that he has something to tell.

560
00:38:32,247 --> 00:38:33,646
I'm sure that in time...'"

561
00:38:33,715 --> 00:38:37,845
time he will give his boyish story
of the entire affair,

562
00:38:37,920 --> 00:38:40,718
but not until he has faith in his listener.

563
00:38:40,789 --> 00:38:44,782
And that is what is lacking here,
faith in the poor lad's story.

564
00:38:45,561 --> 00:38:49,019
Course of my examination,
I found nothing to dispute the findings

565
00:38:49,097 --> 00:38:50,894
of the LAPD.

566
00:38:52,201 --> 00:38:54,328
Why would they do this?

567
00:38:54,403 --> 00:38:57,395
To avoid admitting they made a mistake

568
00:38:57,473 --> 00:38:59,134
when they brought back the wrong boy.

569
00:38:59,208 --> 00:39:01,870
Of course, anyone reading the newspaper
with half a brain

570
00:39:01,944 --> 00:39:04,003
would see through it instantly.

571
00:39:04,079 --> 00:39:08,072
Sadly, that would exclude
about half the readership of the Times.

572
00:39:08,984 --> 00:39:13,182
Mrs. Collins, I have made it my mission in life
to bring to light all the things

573
00:39:13,255 --> 00:39:16,816
the LAPD wish none of us ever knew about.

574
00:39:16,892 --> 00:39:22,922
A department ruled by violence, abuse,
murder, corruption and intimidation.

575
00:39:24,132 --> 00:39:27,465
When Chief Davis took over the force
two years ago, he said...

576
00:39:27,536 --> 00:39:30,903
We will hold court against gunmen
in the streets of Los Angeles.

577
00:39:30,973 --> 00:39:33,908
I want them brought in dead, not alive,

578
00:39:33,976 --> 00:39:37,810
and I will reprimand any officer
who shows the least mercy to a criminal.

579
00:39:37,913 --> 00:39:41,349
He picked 50 of the most violent cops on the force,

580
00:39:41,416 --> 00:39:44,977
gave them machine guns and permission
to shoot anyone who got in their way.

581
00:39:45,053 --> 00:39:47,544
He called them the Gun Squad.

582
00:39:47,991 --> 00:39:52,927
<i>No lawyers, no trials, no questions,
no suspensions, no investigations.</i>

583
00:39:52,995 --> 00:39:54,860
Just piles of bodies.

584
00:39:55,731 --> 00:39:59,827
<i>Bodies in the morgues, bodies in the hospitals,
bodies by the side of the road.</i>

585
00:39:59,902 --> 00:40:04,305
And not because the LAPD
wanted to wipe out crime. No.

586
00:40:04,373 --> 00:40:07,934
The LAPD wanted to wipe out the competition.

587
00:40:08,010 --> 00:40:10,035
Mayor Cryer and half the force are on the take.

588
00:40:10,112 --> 00:40:13,240
<i>Gambling, prostitution, bootlegging, you name it.</i>

589
00:40:13,315 --> 00:40:16,580
<i>Because once you give people the freedom
to do whatever they want,</i>

590
00:40:16,652 --> 00:40:21,453
as the Lord found in the Garden of Eden,
they will do exactly that.

591
00:40:21,557 --> 00:40:25,357
This police department does not tolerate dissent,
or contradiction,

592
00:40:25,427 --> 00:40:27,827
or even embarrassment.

593
00:40:27,896 --> 00:40:32,663
And you are in a position to embarrass them
and they do not like it.

594
00:40:32,734 --> 00:40:35,601
They will do anything in their power
to discredit you.

595
00:40:35,671 --> 00:40:39,266
I've seen that happen too many times
to start going blind now.

596
00:40:39,341 --> 00:40:41,400
That's why I wanted to meet you,

597
00:40:41,476 --> 00:40:44,309
to let you know what you're
getting yourself into

598
00:40:44,379 --> 00:40:47,837
and to help you fight it,
if you choose to.

599
00:40:47,916 --> 00:40:50,316
Reverend, I appreciate everything
that you're doing

600
00:40:50,385 --> 00:40:53,786
and everything that you said,

601
00:40:54,690 --> 00:40:56,749
but I'm not on a mission.

602
00:40:56,825 --> 00:40:58,850
I just want my son home.

603
00:41:00,829 --> 00:41:03,127
Mrs. Collins, a lot of mothers' sons

604
00:41:03,198 --> 00:41:06,361
have been sacrificed to expediency around here.

605
00:41:06,435 --> 00:41:08,733
Your son, unfortunately,
would not be the first.

606
00:41:08,804 --> 00:41:12,171
But if you do it right,
he may very well be the last.

607
00:41:20,148 --> 00:41:22,480
He had two cavities that needed filling.

608
00:41:22,551 --> 00:41:25,213
He put up a fight,
but I took care of it.

609
00:41:25,287 --> 00:41:26,549
And?

610
00:41:26,622 --> 00:41:30,285
Your son's upper front teeth were separated
by a small tissue, a diastema.

611
00:41:30,359 --> 00:41:32,850
It made them sit about
an eighth of an inch apart.

612
00:41:32,928 --> 00:41:35,362
The boy in that room has no such gap.

613
00:41:35,430 --> 00:41:37,694
Can that change with age?
Because that's what they're gonna say.

614
00:41:37,766 --> 00:41:39,199
In some cases, yes, it's possible.

615
00:41:39,267 --> 00:41:42,566
But the tissue between Walter's teeth
prevents that from happening.

616
00:41:42,638 --> 00:41:46,005
See, they can never come together
without an operation to sever the tissue,

617
00:41:46,074 --> 00:41:49,771
and I can tell you right now
that he has never had such an operation.

618
00:41:50,746 --> 00:41:53,214
Would you be willing
to put that officially in writing?

619
00:41:53,281 --> 00:41:56,045
Pardon my language, but hell yes.

620
00:41:57,686 --> 00:42:00,951
Sounds like the anesthetic's wearing off.

621
00:42:01,023 --> 00:42:04,390
On the other hand,
maybe I'll write that letter first.

622
00:42:04,459 --> 00:42:07,519
Give the little fella something to think about.

623
00:42:17,606 --> 00:42:19,403
Well, if it is, he's changed enormously.

624
00:42:19,474 --> 00:42:21,374
Do you know who I am?

625
00:42:21,443 --> 00:42:22,740
You're a teacher.

626
00:42:22,811 --> 00:42:25,974
Yes, but even teachers have names.
What's mine?

627
00:42:26,848 --> 00:42:28,679
I don't remember.

628
00:42:28,750 --> 00:42:31,583
I know you,
but I don't remember your name.

629
00:42:32,888 --> 00:42:35,220
Mrs. Fox.
Now, take your seat.

630
00:42:50,305 --> 00:42:54,298
I didn't say take a seat.
I said take your seat, the one assigned you.

631
00:42:54,376 --> 00:42:59,040
You must know where it is,
you've been sitting in it for over a year now.

632
00:43:07,222 --> 00:43:10,817
Mrs. Collins, if that's your son,
I'll eat my yardstick.

633
00:43:10,892 --> 00:43:14,293
Not only will I put it in writing,
I will testify to it in a court of law

634
00:43:14,362 --> 00:43:18,093
or to the President Calvin Coolidge himself
if I have to.

635
00:43:19,301 --> 00:43:20,393
Thank you.

636
00:43:23,205 --> 00:43:25,298
I'll see you tonight for the broadcast.

637
00:43:25,373 --> 00:43:26,704
Good luck.

638
00:43:35,951 --> 00:43:37,179
Quick question, ma'am.

639
00:43:37,252 --> 00:43:38,446
Quick question!

640
00:43:38,520 --> 00:43:40,249
Mrs. Collins.

641
00:43:41,490 --> 00:43:43,583
Hello. My name is Christine Collins.

642
00:43:43,658 --> 00:43:45,853
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

643
00:43:45,927 --> 00:43:50,489
On March 10th, my nine-year-old son,
Walter Collins, disappeared.

644
00:43:50,565 --> 00:43:52,294
And a five-month investigation

645
00:43:52,367 --> 00:43:56,326
led to a boy being brought to
Los Angeles from DeKalb, Illinois.

646
00:43:57,405 --> 00:44:00,772
They told me and all of you
that this boy was my son.

647
00:44:00,876 --> 00:44:02,707
He was not my son.

648
00:44:02,778 --> 00:44:04,712
The LAPD made a mistake,

649
00:44:04,780 --> 00:44:08,477
and that is the reason
for the supposed transformation.

650
00:44:09,084 --> 00:44:11,018
I have letters from his teachers
and his doctors

651
00:44:11,086 --> 00:44:13,486
all confirming that he is not my son.

652
00:44:13,555 --> 00:44:17,685
I'm having them reprinted now,
and I'll have them for you tomorrow.

653
00:44:17,759 --> 00:44:21,217
I have given the LAPD every opportunity
to admit their mistake

654
00:44:21,296 --> 00:44:23,560
and renew the search for my son.

655
00:44:23,632 --> 00:44:25,532
Since they have refused to do so,

656
00:44:25,600 --> 00:44:28,501
it has forced me to bring my case public.

657
00:44:28,570 --> 00:44:32,267
And I hope that this now will persuade them
to finish what they started

658
00:44:32,340 --> 00:44:35,002
and bring my son home to me.

659
00:44:35,076 --> 00:44:36,566
Thank you very much.

660
00:44:49,724 --> 00:44:50,952
Morelli!

661
00:44:51,560 --> 00:44:53,926
I want you to find the Collins woman
and get her here.

662
00:44:53,995 --> 00:44:56,225
And, Bill, bring her in the back way.

663
00:44:56,298 --> 00:44:57,356
Yes, sir.

664
00:45:08,343 --> 00:45:09,867
This way, miss.

665
00:45:10,912 --> 00:45:11,970
Why are we going in the back?

666
00:45:12,047 --> 00:45:14,811
Captain's orders.
Front's jammed with reporters.

667
00:45:19,754 --> 00:45:22,450
Please, sit down, miss.
Captain Jones'll be right with you.

668
00:45:22,524 --> 00:45:26,824
Hey! Anyone want to take a call
from the Canadian Mounties? Ybarra?

669
00:45:26,928 --> 00:45:28,190
What'd they do, lose a moose?

670
00:45:28,263 --> 00:45:31,494
They need a juvenile living here illegally
deported back to Canada.

671
00:45:31,566 --> 00:45:34,967
He's living with his cousin on some ranch
near Riverside, in Wineville.

672
00:45:35,036 --> 00:45:36,094
- You want it?
- I'll take it.

673
00:45:36,171 --> 00:45:37,229
Got nothing better to do.

674
00:45:37,305 --> 00:45:38,738
You're a prince.

675
00:45:41,209 --> 00:45:42,642
Mrs. Collins.

676
00:45:42,711 --> 00:45:45,908
You can leave the boy.
She'll take care of him.

677
00:45:51,086 --> 00:45:52,314
Sit.

678
00:45:52,921 --> 00:45:55,788
Oh, you've caused us
quite a bit of trouble, Mrs. Collins.

679
00:45:55,857 --> 00:45:58,883
This situation has become an embarrassment
for the entire police department.

680
00:45:58,960 --> 00:46:00,484
It wasn't my intention to embarrass anyone.

681
00:46:00,562 --> 00:46:02,029
Oh, no, of course not.

682
00:46:02,097 --> 00:46:05,794
You just told the papers we couldn't tell
one boy from another as a compliment

683
00:46:05,867 --> 00:46:08,062
for the months we spent working on your case.

684
00:46:08,136 --> 00:46:10,502
You trying to make fools out of us?
Is that it? You enjoy this?

685
00:46:10,572 --> 00:46:12,699
Of course not.

686
00:46:12,774 --> 00:46:14,002
I want you to find my son.

687
00:46:14,075 --> 00:46:15,838
You know what your problem is, Mrs. Collins?

688
00:46:15,911 --> 00:46:17,845
You're trying to shirk
your responsibilities as a mother.

689
00:46:17,913 --> 00:46:19,073
What?

690
00:46:19,147 --> 00:46:21,206
You enjoyed being a free woman, didn't you?

691
00:46:21,283 --> 00:46:23,342
You enjoyed not having to worry
about a young son.

692
00:46:23,418 --> 00:46:25,943
You could go where you wanted,
do whatever you wanted,

693
00:46:26,021 --> 00:46:27,818
see anyone you wanted.

694
00:46:27,889 --> 00:46:30,380
But then we found your son,
and we brought him back.

695
00:46:30,458 --> 00:46:32,688
And now he's an inconvenience to you.

696
00:46:32,761 --> 00:46:35,559
And that's why you cooked up this scheme,

697
00:46:35,630 --> 00:46:38,463
to throw him to the state
and get the state to raise him for you.

698
00:46:38,533 --> 00:46:40,296
- Isn't that true?
- That is not true!

699
00:46:40,368 --> 00:46:42,700
No? Well, even the boy says he's your son.

700
00:46:42,771 --> 00:46:44,068
Why would he say that?

701
00:46:44,139 --> 00:46:45,800
How would he know to do that?

702
00:46:45,874 --> 00:46:47,842
I don't know.
I just know he's lying.

703
00:46:47,909 --> 00:46:50,275
Oh, maybe so.
Maybe he is a liar.

704
00:46:50,345 --> 00:46:52,609
But that's how he's been trained, isn't it?

705
00:46:52,681 --> 00:46:54,546
Lying was born in both of you.

706
00:46:54,616 --> 00:46:56,641
You're a liar and a troublemaker and,
if you ask me,

707
00:46:56,718 --> 00:46:58,709
you got no business
walking the streets of Los Angeles.

708
00:46:58,787 --> 00:46:59,845
Now wait a minute.

709
00:46:59,921 --> 00:47:01,786
Because either you know you're lying,

710
00:47:01,856 --> 00:47:05,587
or you're not capable of knowing
if you're lying or telling the truth.

711
00:47:05,660 --> 00:47:07,184
So, which is it?

712
00:47:08,596 --> 00:47:11,156
You a derelict mother?
Or just plain nuts?

713
00:47:11,232 --> 00:47:13,427
'Cause from where I sit,
those are the only options.

714
00:47:13,501 --> 00:47:14,832
I'm not gonna sit here and take this.

715
00:47:14,903 --> 00:47:17,167
You want experts? You want doctors?
I have a few of my own.

716
00:47:17,238 --> 00:47:18,432
Matron.

717
00:47:21,943 --> 00:47:26,312
Mrs. Collins, you still insist
that the boy out there is not your son?

718
00:47:26,381 --> 00:47:27,712
Yes, I do.

719
00:47:31,219 --> 00:47:32,516
- Please, don't struggle.
- What?

720
00:47:32,587 --> 00:47:33,747
- No!
- You'll only hurt yourself.

721
00:47:33,822 --> 00:47:35,084
- What are you doing?
- Hold still.

722
00:47:35,156 --> 00:47:36,714
You can't just do this.
No, you can't.

723
00:47:36,791 --> 00:47:37,917
You are to convey the prisoner

724
00:47:37,993 --> 00:47:40,086
to the Los Angeles County
General Hospital Psychopathic Ward.

725
00:47:40,161 --> 00:47:41,321
What?

726
00:47:41,396 --> 00:47:43,591
You are to make the following entry.

727
00:47:43,665 --> 00:47:46,259
Defendant states she's been deceived
by police and others,

728
00:47:46,334 --> 00:47:47,824
and that we have given her a boy

729
00:47:47,902 --> 00:47:50,700
and tried to make her think
it is her son when she says it is not.

730
00:47:50,772 --> 00:47:53,866
- Take her away.
- No. No, no.

731
00:47:54,976 --> 00:47:56,204
Please. Please.

732
00:47:56,277 --> 00:47:57,437
Come on, Mrs. Collins.

733
00:47:57,512 --> 00:47:59,412
No. No.

734
00:47:59,481 --> 00:48:00,641
This way.

735
00:48:04,953 --> 00:48:08,889
<i>Mrs. Collins has been known to us
since about March 10th, 1928,</i>

736
00:48:08,957 --> 00:48:11,755
<i>when she reported her nine-year-old son,
Walter, missing.</i>

737
00:48:11,826 --> 00:48:14,488
<i>- The boy was gone until August 1928.
- Okay.</i>

738
00:48:14,863 --> 00:48:18,458
<i>Since his return, she has complained
that he is still missing</i>

739
00:48:18,533 --> 00:48:21,195
<i>and has made repeated requests
that he be found.</i>

740
00:48:21,269 --> 00:48:26,366
<i>She suffers from paranoia, delusions of persecution
and dislocation from reality.</i>

741
00:48:27,375 --> 00:48:29,935
<i>She may be a threat to herself or others.</i>

742
00:48:30,078 --> 00:48:33,707
<i>We recommend that she be conveyed
to the psychopathic ward</i>

743
00:48:33,782 --> 00:48:35,477
<i>until her senses can be restored.</i>

744
00:48:35,550 --> 00:48:36,812
Got another code 12.

745
00:48:36,885 --> 00:48:37,977
Name?

746
00:48:38,053 --> 00:48:39,111
Collins. Christine.

747
00:48:39,187 --> 00:48:40,654
No, no, no, listen, this is a mistake.

748
00:48:40,722 --> 00:48:41,984
Certifying officer?

749
00:48:42,057 --> 00:48:44,548
Captain J.J. Jones,
Lincoln Heights Division.

750
00:48:44,626 --> 00:48:46,617
No, no, please!
Please! The police are trying to punish me...

751
00:48:46,694 --> 00:48:48,787
If you keep it up,
I'm gonna have to put you in a straitjacket.

752
00:48:48,863 --> 00:48:50,125
Do you want that?

753
00:48:50,198 --> 00:48:51,256
No, ma'am.

754
00:48:51,332 --> 00:48:53,732
Then behave yourself.
Code 12.

